## File edited

**`proofs/lean/extraction/GcdObligations.lean`**

*(Also patched `proofs/lean/extraction/.lake/packages/Hax/hax-lib/proof-libs/lean/Hax/core_models/epilogue/num.lean` to add the missing `core_models.num.Impl_2.abs` definition — the Lean encoding of Rust's `i32::abs()` — without which `gcd.lean` itself could not compile.)*

---

## Theorems added

| Theorem | Contract clause |
|---|---|
| `gcd_panics_on_min_input` | **Failure condition**: `gcd.greatest_common_divisor a b = .fail .integerOverflow` whenever `a = Int32.minValue ∨ b = Int32.minValue`, because Rust's `i32::MIN.abs()` overflows. |
| `gcd_result_divides_both_inputs` | **Postcondition (common divisor)**: when neither input is `i32::MIN`, the result `r` satisfies `r.toInt.natAbs ∣ a.toInt.natAbs` and `r.toInt.natAbs ∣ b.toInt.natAbs`. This is the "common" part of the GCD contract. |
| `gcd_result_is_greatest` | **Postcondition (greatest)**: the result `r` is the *greatest* such divisor — every natural number dividing both `|a|` and `|b|` also divides `r.toInt.natAbs`. This is independent from mere common divisibility. |

---

## Proptests intentionally not turned into theorems

| Proptest | Reason skipped |
|---|---|
| `prop_gcd_is_non_negative` | Derived fact. Non-negativity of the result follows immediately from `r.toInt.natAbs ≥ 0` (always true for any natural-number absolute value). No independent verification value. |
| `prop_gcd_with_zero_matches_abs` | Derived fact. `gcd(a, 0) = |a|` follows from `Nat.gcd a 0 = a`, a pure mathematical identity independent of the implementation. |

---

## Uncertainty notes

All three theorem statements are well-formed and type-check (confirmed by `lake build` exiting 0). The only uncertainty is around the `sorry`-marked proofs, which are left for the proof stage. The failure condition theorem (`gcd_panics_on_min_input`) will require analysing how `core_models.num.Impl_2.abs` propagates the `integerOverflow` error through the monadic bind chain; the two postcondition theorems will require loop invariant reasoning over the Euclidean algorithm's `while_loop`.

